President Donald Trump has issued a proclamation declaring November 2019 as National Native American Heritage Month in the United States. The proclamation recognizes the contributions made by American Indians and Alaska Natives to the nation and honors their sacrifices in defense of the country. It also acknowledges the special government-to-government relationship between the United States and Indian tribes, and reaffirms the commitment to work with tribal communities to address their issues and protect their heritage. The proclamation highlights the high rate of military service among American Indians and Alaska Natives, spanning the history of the nation. The administration's efforts include addressing the drug crisis, improving healthcare access and safety, and holding public safety listening sessions with tribal leaders. The proclamation also mentions the return of ancestral remains and artifacts to pueblos and tribes in the Mesa Verde region. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to commemorate the month with appropriate programs and activities and to celebrate November 29, 2019, as Native American Heritage Day.